            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_237gc' title='Col. 237GC &mdash; HL Deb 06 February 2001 vol 621 c237GC' name='column_237gc' href='#column_237gc' rel='bookmark'>237GC</a>
            education. The Minister's point of view would prevent that difference from being provided. If a deaf child needs a hearing aid or some assistance, they are having no education either. Will my noble friend think again about the issue? I recognise what she said about the other provisions and the other means of tackling it. The amendment is wrong, but the Government should accept the point that has been made and address it on Report. I should like a warm response from the Government.
          </p>
